Write a C++ program to simulate a traffic light system using enum:
Define an enum Colors with values: RED, YELLOW, GREEN. You may assign numbers manually if needed (e.g., RED=1).
Prompt the user to enter a color code representing the traffic light:
RED â†’ 1 YELLOW â†’ 2 GREEN â†’ 3
Use control structures (if-else or switch-case) to print the corresponding action for the traffic light:
RED â†’ Stop ğŸš¦ YELLOW â†’ Wait â³ GREEN â†’ Go ğŸƒâ€â™‚ï¸
If the user enters an invalid code, print "Invalid".'

#include<iostream>
#include<string>
using namespace std;
enum Colors {RED=0,YELLOW=1,GREEN=2};
int main() {
   int num;
    cout<<"Enter the colour : ";
    cin>>num;
        switch(num) {
    case 0: cout << "STOP"; break;
    case 1: cout << "WAIT"; break;
    case 2: cout << "GO"; break;
}
return 0;
}
